Here is a simple C++ program that multiplies two matrices:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

const int ROWS1 = 2;
const int COLS1 = 3;
const int ROWS2 = 3;
const int COLS2 = 2;

int main() {
    int matrix1[ROWS1][COLS1] = {{1, 2, 3}, {4, 5, 6}};
    int matrix2[ROWS2][COLS2] = {{7, 8}, {9, 10}, {11, 12}};
    int product[ROWS1][COLS2] = {{0, 0}, {0, 0}};

    // Multiply matrices
    for (int i = 0; i < ROWS1; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < COLS2; j++) {
            for (int k = 0; k < COLS1; k++) {
                product[i][j] += matrix1[i][k] * matrix2[k][j];
            }
        }
    }

    // Display product matrix
    cout << "Product of matrices:" << endl;
    for (int i = 0; i < ROWS1; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < COLS2; j++) {
            cout << product[i][j] << " ";
        }
        cout << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this program, we first define the input matrices and the output product matrix. Then, we iterate over the matrices to compute the product matrix as the multiplication of the two input matrices. Finally, we display the product matrix. Note that in the multiplication loop, we use a third index variable `k` to iterate over elements within each row/column.

